        "<p>A Mad Tea-Party</p>\n<p>There was a table set out under a tree in front of the house, and the</p>\n<p>March Hare and the Hatter were having tea at it: a Dormouse was sitting</p>\n<p>between them, fast asleep, and the other two were using it as a</p>\n<p>cushion, resting their elbows on it, and talking over its head.</p>\n<p>â€œVery</p>\n<p>uncomfortable for the Dormouse,â€ thought Alice; â€œonly, as itâ€™s asleep,</p>\n",
        "<p>I suppose it doesnâ€™t mind.â€</p>\n<p>The table was a large one, but the three were all crowded together at</p>\n<p>one corner of it: â€œNo room!</p>\n<p>No room!â€ they cried out when they saw</p>\n<p>Alice coming.</p>\n<p>â€œThereâ€™s _plenty_ of room!â€ said Alice indignantly, and</p>\n<p>she sat down in a large arm-chair at one end of the table.</p>\n",
